Want to adopt a child7 For most
couples there is a long waiting
period. But, many children of
minority groups are crowding
foster homes and institutions
waiting for adoption.


During the month of May the
Phoenix Urban League and the
state department of public well
fare are hoping to promote more
adoptions of minority groups
children.


The Urban League has speak
er and a film on adoption through
a licensed agency which can be
presented to interested organi-
cations.


For further Information con-
corning the film, speaker or pro-
cedures to adopt children, call
the Urban League office
CIR 7-542l or the public welfare
department 27l-444l.

DR.. William Joseph Moore,
state health commissioner urges
persons to have measles vaci-
nations.


Red or ordinary measles, in
contrast to German measles, is
serious disease which annually
takes about 500 lives a year in
the United States, he said.


Immunization, he said, would
prepare one for the disease S on
slaught in late winter or early
spring next year.


There we're 430 red measles
cases reported on May l to the
state health department. This
compares with the 353 cases re-
ported the preceding week.


Although there is no vaccine
for German measles, he said,
there are three vaccines, includ-
ing the live attenuated vaccine
with gamma globulin, that i'm
munize against red measles, DR..
Moore said.
